        "isCorrect": true,
        "text": "は comes right after the topic to show what the sentence is about"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "That’s true in these examples, but that’s the meaning of the sentences—not the grammar job of は. Look at where は appears and what it’s doing.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "は means “is/are”"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "In these sentences, は is pronounced “wa,” not “ha.” More importantly, notice its position: it follows the topic.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "は is always pronounced “ha”"
      },
      {
        "feedback": "Not here—は appears in the middle, right after the topic. The sentence usually continues after は.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "は always comes at the end of a sentence"
      }
    ],
    "question": "What pattern do you notice about the highlighted は in these sentences?"
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "highlight": "は",
      "romanization": "watashi wa gakusei desu.",
      "sentence": "私は学生です。",
      "translation": "I am a student."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "は",
      "romanization": "kore wa hon desu.",
      "sentence": "これは本です。",
      "translation": "This is a book."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "は",
      "romanization": "Tanaka-san wa sensei desu.",
      "sentence": "田中さんは先生です。",
      "translation": "Mr. Tanaka is a teacher."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "は",
      "romanization": "nihon wa atsui desu.",
      "sentence": "日本は暑いです。",
      "translation": "Japan is hot."
