  "ruleName": "Spanish Present Tense: Regular -ar Verb Endings",
  "ruleSummary": "In these examples, regular **-ar** verbs keep the same stem and change the ending to match the subject (trabaj-o, trabaj-a, estudi-amos, estudi-an). This is present-tense verb conjugation."
}

{
  "discovery": {
    "options": [
      {
        "feedback": "Correct. In each sentence, exactly one element comes first (a time phrase, an object, or the subject), and then the conjugated verb comes next.",
        "isCorrect": true,
        "text": "In these main clauses, the conjugated verb is always in the 2nd position, even if the sentence starts with something other than the subject."
      },
      {
        "feedback": "That’s true in some examples, but it’s not the key pattern. Look at where the verb is placed when the sentence starts with Heute / Den Film / In Berlin.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "German sentences always start with the subject."
      },
      {
        "feedback": "You do see time/place phrases at the beginning, but that’s optional. The consistent pattern is what happens to the conjugated verb right after the first element.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "A time or place phrase must come first in German sentences."
      },
      {
        "feedback": "Not here: in each example the verb comes before the subject when a different element (like Heute or Den Film) is in first position. The key is that the verb stays second.",
        "isCorrect": false,
        "text": "In German main clauses, the subject always comes before the verb."
      }
    ],
    "question": "What pattern do you notice in the highlighted parts of these sentences?"
  },
  "examples": [
    {
      "highlight": "gehe ich",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Heute **gehe ich** ins Kino.",
      "translation": "Today I’m going to the movies."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "kauft er",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Morgen **kauft er** Brot.",
      "translation": "Tomorrow he buys bread."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "sehen wir",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "Den Film **sehen wir** am Abend.",
      "translation": "We’re watching the movie in the evening."
    },
    {
      "highlight": "arbeitet sie",
      "romanization": "",
      "sentence": "In Berlin **arbeitet sie**.",
      "translation": "In Berlin she works."
    }
  ],
  "exercises": [
    {
      "answers": [
        "trinke ich"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "ich trinke",
        "trinken ich",
        "trinkt ich"
      ],
      "feedback": "With a first-position element like \"Jetzt\", the conjugated verb comes next (2nd position): \"Jetzt trinke ich ...\"",
      "template": "Jetzt [BLANK] Kaffee."
    },
    {
      "answers": [
        "macht er"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "er macht",
        "machen er",
        "macht ihn"
      ],
      "feedback": "When the sentence starts with \"Am Sonntag\", the verb still stays in 2nd position: \"Am Sonntag macht er ...\"",
      "template": "Am Sonntag [BLANK] Sport."
    },
    {
      "answers": [
        "besuchen wir"
      ],
      "distractors": [
        "wir besuchen",
        "besucht wir",
        "besuchen wirs"
      ],
      "feedback": "With an object in first position (\"Meine Freundin\"), the conjugated verb comes next: \"Meine Freundin besuchen wir ...\"",
      "template": "Meine Freundin [BLANK] heute."
    }
  ],
  "ruleName": "German Verb-Second (V2) Word Order in Main Clauses",
  "ruleSummary": "In German main clauses, the conjugated verb is in the 2nd position. If something other than the subject is in 1st position, the subject moves after the verb."
}

